{"title_page": "Concordia Hospital", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox hospital\n| Name       = Concordia Hospital\n| Org/Group  = [[Winnipeg Regional Health Authority]]\n| Image      = Entrance to Concordia Hospital in Winnipeg, Manitoba.jpg\n| caption    = Entrance to Concordia Hospital\n| Logo       = <!-- optional -->\n| Location   = 1095 Concordia Avenue\n| Region     = Winnipeg\n| State      = Manitoba\n| Country    = Canada\n{{coord|49.9132|-97.0646|type:landmark_region:CA-MB|display=inline,title}}\n| mapframe-zoom   = 14\n| HealthCare = Medicare\n| Type       = Non-teaching\n| Speciality = \n| Standards  = <!-- optional if no national standards -->\n| Emergency  = No\n| Affiliation= None\n| Beds       =  185\n| Founded    =  1928 \n| Closed     = <!-- optional -->\n| Website    = {{URL|www.concordiahospital.mb.ca}}\n| Wiki-Links = <!-- optional -->\n|}}\n'''Concordia Hospital''' is a regional [[hospital]] in [[Winnipeg]], [[Manitoba]] that was founded in 1928,<ref>{{cite web|title=Our History|url=http://www.concordiahospital.mb.ca/foundation/history.html|publisher=Concordia Foundation|accessdate=14 October 2012}}</ref> and has a primary service area with a population exceeding 150,000.<ref>{{cite web|title=Concordia Hospital Pharmacy Department  Pharmacy Student Placement Description|url=http://www.wrha.mb.ca/prog/pharmacy/files/practplacedescr-ch.pdf|publisher=Winnipeg Regional Health Authority|accessdate=15 October 2012|date=June 2010}}</ref>\n\nBetween April 2011 and March 2012, Concordia hospital provided 1,507 hip and knee surgeries, nearly 50% more than any other Winnipeg facility.<ref>{{cite web|title=Summary of All Hip & Knee Surgeries|url=https://www.gov.mb.ca/health/waittime/surgical/all_hipknee.html|publisher=Government of Manitoba|accessdate=15 October 2012|date=August 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe hospital's name originates from a poem entitled \"Song of the Church Bell\" by German poet and philosopher [[Friedrich Schiller]].  The inspirational line reads, \"Concordia shall be her name; to harmony, to hearty fellowship, it summons the cherished community.\"<ref name=Connect/>\n\n==History==\nThe \"Concordia Society\" was founded in 1928 as a maternity hospital in a private home on Machray Avenue in [[West Kildonan, Winnipeg|West Kildonan]].<ref name=Connect>{{cite web|title=Connect... the Concordia Way|url=http://concordiafoundation.ca/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/Connect0902.pdf|publisher=Concordia Hospital|accessdate=14 October 2012|pages=24|date=February 2009}}</ref>  The original facilities included five beds and the hospital had a staff of three people.<ref name=Connect/> The first year saw 28 mothers admitted to the hospital, and by the second year the admissions had increased to 100.<ref name=Connect/>\n\nIn 1930, the hospital was renamed \"Mennonite Concordia Hospital\" and was operated by a Board of Directors.<ref name=Connect/>\n\nOn 26 March 1931, the hospital was granted official incorporation by the Government of Manitoba.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Concordia Hospital Incorporation Act|url=http://web2.gov.mb.ca/laws/statutes/private/c03990e.php|publisher=Government of Manitoba|accessdate=15 October 2012|date=2 October 2012}}</ref> On 13 July 1931, a new site was dedicated for the hospital.<ref name=Connect/> During the first eleven months of operation at the new location, the hospital admitted 297 patients.<ref name=Connect/>  Of these, 113 were maternity patients, 114 were surgical patients, 67 were medical and 3 were admitted for bone fractures.<ref name=Connect/>\n\nIn 1933, the hospital purchased the Elmwood Sanitorium.<ref name=Connect/> The hospital expanded in 1953 and 1958.<ref name=Connect/>\n\nIn 1964, the hospital purchased the land which became the current location of the hospital.<ref name=Connect/> In 1974 the location opened with 124 beds.<ref name=Connect/> In 1985 the Emergency Department of the location was expanded.<ref name=Connect/>\n\nIn 2005, the Manitoba government made the hospital a centre of excellence in hip and knee replacements.\n\nThe hospital's Emergency Room underwent a $3.6-million renovation in 2008,<ref>{{cite web|title=Premier Officially Opens New Concordia Hospital Emergency Department|url=http://news.gov.mb.ca/news/index.html?item=4838|publisher=Winnipeg Regional Health Authority|accessdate=15 October 2012|date=28 November 2008}}</ref> increasing the size by nearly {{convert|2000|sqft|m2}}.<ref name=Connect/> The renovation included increased space for the triage area, minor treatment rooms and admitting desk, as well as the addition of counseling rooms and improvement of the medication rooms.<ref name=Connect/> The upgrades included the addition of an Emergency Department Information System (EDIS) which tracks information on patients that visit the ER.<ref name=Connect/>\n\n==Concordia Place==\n[[File:Concordia Place, 1000 Molson Street, Winnipeg Manitoba.jpg|thumb|Concordia Place, 1000 Molson Street, Winnipeg Manitoba]]\nIn 1998, Concordia Hospital built Concordia Place, a personal care home adjacent to the hospital.<ref name=ConcordiaPlaceHistory>{{cite web|title=History of Concordia Place|url=http://www.concordiahospital.mb.ca/place/history.html|publisher=Concordia Hospital|accessdate=14 October 2012}}</ref> Concordia Place opened on 10 May 2000, with 140 beds.<ref name=ConcordiaPlaceHistory/> Staff at Concordia Place include Registered and Licensed Practical Nurses, Health Care Aides, Recreation staff, a Clinical Dietitian, and Occupational Therapist and a Chaplain, among others.<ref name=Connect /> Concordia Place features group activities and recreational programs and a dedicated chapel.<ref name=Connect />\n\n==Concordia Village==\n[[File:Entrance to Concordia Village I, 1125 Molson St, Winnipeg, Manitoba.jpg|thumb|Entrance to Concordia Village I]]\nConcordia Village is an assisted living facility located across from the hospital. The facility includes three buildings: Concordia Village I, Concordia Village II and Concordia Village III.<ref name=ProjectsFacilities>{{cite web|title=Projects/Facilities|url=http://concordiavillage.ca/about/projectsfacilities/|publisher=Concordia Wellness Projects|accessdate=14 October 2012}}</ref> Each facility features both one and two-bedroom apartment units with kitchens, storage and private balconies.<ref name=ProjectsFacilities/> Buildings I and II each have two guest suites for visiting families and other overnight guests.<ref name=ProjectsFacilities/> Concordia Village is owned and operated by Concordia Wellness Projects Inc., a non-profit registered charitable organization.<ref>{{cite web|title=Dedicated to the wellness of seniors\u2026|url=http://concordiavillage.ca/|publisher=Concordia Wellness Projects Inc.|accessdate=14 October 2012}}</ref> Construction costs for the three villages were $12.0 million for Phase I, $16.8 million for Phase II, and $13 million for Phase III.<ref>{{cite web|title=Concordia Village Phase 1, 2 and 3|url=http://www.wgkastes.com/concordia%20village.pdf|publisher=Kastes|accessdate=15 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nVillage I has 94 units and was established in 2006 at 1125 Molson Street.<ref name=ProjectsFacilities/><ref name=Concord>{{cite web|title=Completed Projects - Residential|url=http://www.concordprojects.com/home.asp?type=projectlist&cat=residential&comp=true|publisher=Concord Projects Ltd.|accessdate=15 October 2012|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130119221610/http://www.concordprojects.com/home.asp?type=projectlist&cat=residential&comp=true|archive-date=19 January 2013|url-status = dead}}</ref> Village II has 103 units and was established in 2008 at 1115 Molson Street.<ref name=ProjectsFacilities/><ref name=Concord/> Village III has 90 units and was established in 2010 at 1115 Molson Street.<ref name=ProjectsFacilities/><ref name=Concord/>\n\nConcordia Village's services include:<ref>{{cite web|title=Welcome to Concordia Village|url=http://concordiavillage.ca/wp-content/uploads/2012/01/CV_Brochure_vJan2012.pdf|publisher=Concordia Village|accessdate=15 October 2012|date=January 2012}}</ref>\n\n* Dinner meal and continental breakfast\n* Weekly housekeeping and daily garbage collection \n* Personal security device\n* Planned social/recreational activities and excursions\n* Visiting home care workers\n* Hair salons \n* Monthly banking with [[Steinbach Credit Union]] (SCU)\n* [[ATM machines]]\n\n==Concordia Hip and Knee Institute==\nIn 2009 at Concordia Hospital opened a {{convert|60000|sqft|m2}} building to house the Hip and Knee Institute.<ref name=Connect /><ref name=WRHA>{{cite web|title=Concordia Hip & Knee Institute receives $10 million|url=http://www.wrha.mb.ca/healthinfo/news/2011/110316.php|publisher=WinnipegHealthRegion.ca|accessdate=14 October 2012}}</ref> The building includes a [[Shoppers Drug Mart]].<ref name=Connect /> The third level is completely dedicated to the Hip and Knee Institute.<ref name=Connect /> The institute is home to a hip and knee assessment clinic, a digital imaging clinic, a research facility, a research laboratory, a training and education facility and a pre-habilitation clinic.<ref name=WRHA/> The institute has a knee surgical simulator suite, a scanning [[electron microscope]], a digital X-ray lab and an implants retrieval lab.<ref name=WRHA/> The implants retrieval lab provides storage for worn-out replacement hip and knee joints for studying patterns of failure.<ref name=WRHA/> The institute features a conference centre connected to an operating room where surgical procedures can be viewed on a television screen.<ref name=WRHA/>\n\n==Hand washing audit==\nA hand-hygiene audit completed in February 2012 found that front-line staff in hospitals do not sufficiently wash their hands.<ref name=Handwashing>{{cite news|last=Welch|first=Mary Agnes|title=Many health-care workers don't wash their hands as often as they should|url=http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/local/interactive-handwashing-compliance-in-winnipeg-personal-care-homes-160044435.html?viewAllComments=y|accessdate=14 October 2012|newspaper=[[Winnipeg Free Press]]|date=23 June 2012}}</ref> Reports reviewed two wards, N2W and N2E, and found compliance rates of only 58% and 48%.<ref name=Handwashing/>\n\n==Superbug outbreaks==\nConcordia Hospital has been involved in outbreaks of highly contagious viruses and antibiotic-resistant [[Antimicrobial resistance|superbugs]].<ref name=Superbugs>{{cite news|last=Skerritt|first=Jen|title=Hospital outbreaks kept quiet|url=http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/business/hospital-outbreaks-kept-quiet-42890912.html|accessdate=14 October 2012|newspaper=[[Winnipeg Free Press]]|date=13 April 2009}}</ref> Based on data released covering 2006 through 2008: in 2007, the hospital saw 42 people infected with [[Methicillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus|MRSA]] and 30 people infected with [[Norovirus]], and in 2006 the hospital saw 82 Norovirus infections.<ref name=Superbugs/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|33em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.concordiahospital.mb.ca/ Concordia Hospital]\n* [http://www.wrha.mb.ca/prog/ipc/outbreaks.php List of current outbreaks in Winnipeg Health Region facilities]\n* [https://www.gov.mb.ca/health/waittime/surgical/all_hipknee.html Wait Times for Hip & Knee Surgeries]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Hospitals in Winnipeg]]\n[[Category:Hospital buildings completed in 1931]]\n[[Category:Hospital buildings completed in 1974]]\n[[Category:Hospitals established in 1928]]\n[[Category:1928 establishments in Manitoba]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox hospital\n| Name       = Concordia Hospital\n| Org/Group  = [[Winnipeg Regional Health Authority]]\n| Image      = Entrance to Concordia Hospital in Winnipeg, Manitoba.jpg\n| caption    = Entrance to Concordia Hospital\n| Logo       = <!-- optional -->\n| Location   = 1095 Concordia Avenue\n| Region     = Winnipeg\n| State      = Manitoba\n| Country    = Canada\n{{coord|49.9132|-97.0646|type:landmark_region:CA-MB|display=inline,title}}\n| mapframe-zoom   = 14\n| HealthCare = Medicare\n| Type       = Non-teaching\n| Speciality = \n| Standards  = <!-- optional if no national standards -->\n| Emergency  = No\n| Affiliation= None\n| Beds       =  185\n| Founded    =  1928 \n| Closed     = <!-- optional -->\n| Website    = {{URL|www.concordiahospital.mb.ca}}\n| Wiki-Links = <!-- optional -->\n|}}\n'''Concordia Hospital''' is a regional [[hospital]] in [[Winnipeg]], [[Manitoba]] that was founded in 1928,<ref>{{cite web|title=Our History|url=http://www.concordiahospital.mb.ca/foundation/history.html|publisher=Concordia Foundation|accessdate=14 October 2012}}</ref> and has a primary service area with a population exceeding 150,000.<ref>{{cite web|title=Concordia Hospital Pharmacy Department  Pharmacy Student Placement Description|url=http://www.wrha.mb.ca/prog/pharmacy/files/practplacedescr-ch.pdf|publisher=Winnipeg Regional Health Authority|accessdate=15 October 2012|date=June 2010}}</ref>\n\nBetween April 2011 and March 2012, Concordia hospital provided 1,507 hip and knee surgeries, nearly 50% more than any other Winnipeg facility.<ref>{{cite web|title=Summary of All Hip & Knee Surgeries|url=https://www.gov.mb.ca/health/waittime/surgical/all_hipknee.html|publisher=Government of Manitoba|accessdate=15 October 2012|date=August 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe hospital's name originates from a poem entitled \"Song of the Church Bell\" by German poet and philosopher [[Friedrich Schiller]].  The inspirational line reads, \"Concordia shall be her name; to harmony, to hearty fellowship, it summons the cherished community.\"<ref name=Connect/>\n\n==History==\nThe \"Concordia Society\" was founded in 1928 as a maternity hospital in a private home on Machray Avenue in [[West Kildonan, Winnipeg|West Kildonan]].<ref name=Connect>{{cite web|title=Connect... the Concordia Way|url=http://concordiafoundation.ca/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/Connect0902.pdf|publisher=Concordia Hospital|accessdate=14 October 2012|pages=24|date=February 2009}}</ref>  The original facilities included five beds and the hospital had a staff of three people.<ref name=Connect/> The first year saw 28 mothers admitted to the hospital, and by the second year the admissions had increased to 100.<ref name=Connect/>\n\nIn 1930, the hospital was renamed \"Mennonite Concordia Hospital\" and was operated by a Board of Directors.<ref name=Connect/>\n\nOn 26 March 1931, the hospital was granted official incorporation by the Government of Manitoba.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Concordia Hospital Incorporation Act|url=http://web2.gov.mb.ca/laws/statutes/private/c03990e.php|publisher=Government of Manitoba|accessdate=15 October 2012|date=2 October 2012}}</ref> On 13 July 1931, a new site was dedicated for the hospital.<ref name=Connect/> During the first eleven months of operation at the new location, the hospital admitted 297 patients.<ref name=Connect/>  Of these, 113 were maternity patients, 114 were surgical patients, 67 were medical and 3 were admitted for bone fractures.<ref name=Connect/>\n\nIn 1933, the hospital purchased the Elmwood Sanitorium.<ref name=Connect/> The hospital expanded in 1953 and 1958.<ref name=Connect/>\n\nIn 1964, the hospital purchased the land which became the current location of the hospital.<ref name=Connect/> In 1974 the location opened with 124 beds.<ref name=Connect/> In 1985 the Emergency Department of the location was expanded.<ref name=Connect/>\n\nIn 2005, the Manitoba government made the hospital a centre of excellence in hip and knee replacements.\n\nThe hospital's Emergency Room underwent a $3.6-million renovation in 2008,<ref>{{cite web|title=Premier Officially Opens New Concordia Hospital Emergency Department|url=http://news.gov.mb.ca/news/index.html?item=4838|publisher=Winnipeg Regional Health Authority|accessdate=15 October 2012|date=28 November 2008}}</ref> increasing the size by nearly {{convert|2000|sqft|m2}}.<ref name=Connect/> The renovation included increased space for the triage area, minor treatment rooms and admitting desk, as well as the addition of counseling rooms and improvement of the medication rooms.<ref name=Connect/> The upgrades included the addition of an Emergency Department Information System (EDIS) which tracks information on patients that visit the ER.<ref name=Connect/>\n\n==Concordia Place==\n[[File:Concordia Place, 1000 Molson Street, Winnipeg Manitoba.jpg|thumb|Concordia Place, 1000 Molson Street, Winnipeg Manitoba]]\nIn 1998, Concordia Hospital built Concordia Place, a personal care home adjacent to the hospital.<ref name=ConcordiaPlaceHistory>{{cite web|title=History of Concordia Place|url=http://www.concordiahospital.mb.ca/place/history.html|publisher=Concordia Hospital|accessdate=14 October 2012}}</ref> Concordia Place opened on 10 May 2000, with 140 beds.<ref name=ConcordiaPlaceHistory/> Staff at Concordia Place include Registered and Licensed Practical Nurses, Health Care Aides, Recreation staff, a Clinical Dietitian, and Occupational Therapist and a Chaplain, among others.<ref name=Connect /> Concordia Place features group activities and recreational programs and a dedicated chapel.<ref name=Connect />\n\n==Concordia Village==\n[[File:Entrance to Concordia Village I, 1125 Molson St, Winnipeg, Manitoba.jpg|thumb|Entrance to Concordia Village I]]\nConcordia Village is an assisted living facility located across from the hospital. The facility includes three buildings: Concordia Village I, Concordia Village II and Concordia Village III.<ref name=ProjectsFacilities>{{cite web|title=Projects/Facilities|url=http://concordiavillage.ca/about/projectsfacilities/|publisher=Concordia Wellness Projects|accessdate=14 October 2012}}</ref> Each facility features both one and two-bedroom apartment units with kitchens, storage and private balconies.<ref name=ProjectsFacilities/> Buildings I and II each have two guest suites for visiting families and other overnight guests.<ref name=ProjectsFacilities/> Concordia Village is owned and operated by Concordia Wellness Projects Inc., a non-profit registered charitable organization.<ref>{{cite web|title=Dedicated to the wellness of seniors\u2026|url=http://concordiavillage.ca/|publisher=Concordia Wellness Projects Inc.|accessdate=14 October 2012}}</ref> Construction costs for the three villages were $12.0 million for Phase I, $16.8 million for Phase II, and $13 million for Phase III.<ref>{{cite web|title=Concordia Village Phase 1, 2 and 3|url=http://www.wgkastes.com/concordia%20village.pdf|publisher=Kastes|accessdate=15 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nVillage I has 94 units and was established in 2006 at 1125 Molson Street.<ref name=ProjectsFacilities/><ref name=Concord>{{cite web|title=Completed Projects - Residential|url=http://www.concordprojects.com/home.asp?type=projectlist&cat=residential&comp=true|publisher=Concord Projects Ltd.|accessdate=15 October 2012|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130119221610/http://www.concordprojects.com/home.asp?type=projectlist&cat=residential&comp=true|archive-date=19 January 2013|url-status = dead}}</ref> Village II has 103 units and was established in 2008 at 1115 Molson Street.<ref name=ProjectsFacilities/><ref name=Concord/> Village III has 90 units and was established in 2010 at 1115 Molson Street.<ref name=ProjectsFacilities/><ref name=Concord/>\n\nConcordia Village's services include:<ref>{{cite web|title=Welcome to Concordia Village|url=http://concordiavillage.ca/wp-content/uploads/2012/01/CV_Brochure_vJan2012.pdf|publisher=Concordia Village|accessdate=15 October 2012|date=January 2012}}</ref>\n\n* Dinner meal and continental breakfast\n* Weekly housekeeping and daily garbage collection \n* Personal security device\n* Planned social/recreational activities and excursions\n* Visiting home care workers\n* Hair salons \n* Monthly banking with [[Steinbach Credit Union]] (SCU)\n* [[ATM machines]]\n\n==Concordia Hip and Knee Institute==\nIn 2009 at Concordia Hospital opened a {{convert|60000|sqft|m2}} building to house the Hip and Knee Institute.<ref name=Connect /><ref name=WRHA>{{cite web|title=Concordia Hip & Knee Institute receives $10 million|url=http://www.wrha.mb.ca/healthinfo/news/2011/110316.php|publisher=WinnipegHealthRegion.ca|accessdate=14 October 2012}}</ref> The building includes a [[Shoppers Drug Mart]].<ref name=Connect /> The third level is completely dedicated to the Hip and Knee Institute.<ref name=Connect /> The institute is home to a hip and knee assessment clinic, a digital imaging clinic, a research facility, a research laboratory, a training and education facility and a pre-habilitation clinic.<ref name=WRHA/> The institute has a knee surgical simulator suite, a scanning [[electron microscope]], a digital X-ray lab and an implants retrieval lab.<ref name=WRHA/> The implants retrieval lab provides storage for worn-out replacement hip and knee joints for studying patterns of failure.<ref name=WRHA/> The institute features a conference centre connected to an operating room where surgical procedures can be viewed on a television screen.<ref name=WRHA/>\n\n==Hand washing audit==\nA hand-hygiene audit completed in February 2012 found that front-line staff in hospitals do not sufficiently wash their hands.<ref name=Handwashing>{{cite news|last=Welch|first=Mary Agnes|title=Many health-care workers don't wash their hands as often as they should|url=http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/local/interactive-handwashing-compliance-in-winnipeg-personal-care-homes-160044435.html?viewAllComments=y|accessdate=14 October 2012|newspaper=[[Winnipeg Free Press]]|date=23 June 2012}}</ref> Reports reviewed two wards, N2W and N2E, and found compliance rates of only 58% and 48%.<ref name=Handwashing/>\n\n==Superbug outbreaks==\nConcordia Hospital has been involved in outbreaks of highly contagious viruses and antibiotic-resistant [[Antimicrobial resistance|superbugs]].<ref name=Superbugs>{{cite news|last=Skerritt|first=Jen|title=Hospital outbreaks kept quiet|url=http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/business/hospital-outbreaks-kept-quiet-42890912.html|accessdate=14 October 2012|newspaper=[[Winnipeg Free Press]]|date=13 April 2009}}</ref> Based on data released covering 2006 through 2008: in 2007, the hospital saw 42 people infected with [[Methicillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus|MRSA]] and 30 people infected with [[Norovirus]], and in 2006 the hospital saw 82 Norovirus infections.<ref name=Superbugs/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|33em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.concordiahospital.mb.ca/ Concordia Hospital]\n* [http://www.wrha.mb.ca/prog/ipc/outbreaks.php List of current outbreaks in Winnipeg Health Region facilities]\n* [https://www.gov.mb.ca/health/waittime/surgical/all_hipknee.html Wait Times for Hip & Knee Surgeries]\n\n[[Category:Hospitals in Winnipeg]]\n[[Category:Hospital buildings completed in 1931]]\n[[Category:Hospital buildings completed in 1974]]\n[[Category:Hospitals established in 1928]]\n[[Category:1928 establishments in Manitoba]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Concordia_Hospital"}
{"title_page": "Colwyn Bay Community Hospital", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox hospital\n| Name        = Colwyn Bay Community Hospital\n| Org/Group   = [[Betsi Cadwaladr University Health Board]]\n| Image       = Colwyn Bay Community Hospital (geograph 3286184).jpg\n| Caption     = Colwyn Bay Community Hospital\n| map_type    = Wales Conwy\n| map_caption = Shown in Conwy County Borough\n| Logo        = <!-- optional -->\n| Location    = [[Colwyn Bay]]\n| Region      = Conwy County Borough\n| State       = Wales\n| Country     = UK\n| Coordinates = {{coord|53.2879|-3.7104|display=inline,title}}\n| HealthCare  = NHS\n| Type        = Community hospital\n| Speciality  = <!-- if devoted to a speciality, i.e. not if has broad spectrum of specialities -->\n| Standards   = <!-- optional if no national standards -->\n| Emergency   = \n| Affiliation =\n| Beds        =\n| Staff       = \n| Founded     = 1899\n| Closed      = \n| Website     = \n| Wiki-Links  = <!-- optional -->\n|}}\n'''Colwyn Bay Community Hospital''' ({{lang-cy|Ysbyty Cymuned Bae Colwyn}}) is a [[community hospital]] in [[Colwyn Bay]], Wales. It is managed by the [[Betsi Cadwaladr University Health Board]].\n\n==History==\nThe hospital has its origins in the Colwyn Bay Jubilee Cottage Hospital which was established in 1899.<ref name=na>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/hospitalrecords/details.asp?id=913|title=Colwyn Bay Community Hospital, Colwyn Bay|publisher=National Archives|accessdate=26 February 2019}}</ref> The present hospital, which was designed by Sidney Colwyn Foulkes and incorporated the latest concepts from the United States, opened as the Colwyn Bay and West Denbighshire Hospital in 1925.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://colwynbayheritage.org.uk/sidney-colwyn-foulkes/|title=Sidney Colwyn Foulkes|publisher=Colwyn Bay Heritage|accessdate=26 February 2019}}</ref> It joined the [[National Health Service]] in 1948 and became a community hospital in the 1980s.<ref name=na/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Hospitals established in 1899]]\n[[Category:Hospitals in Conwy County Borough]]\n[[Category:Hospital buildings completed in 1925]]\n[[Category:1899 establishments in Wales]]\n[[Category:NHS hospitals in Wales]]\n[[Category:Betsi Cadwaladr University Health Board]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox hospital\n| Name        = Colwyn Bay Community Hospital\n| Org/Group   = [[Betsi Cadwaladr University Health Board]]\n| Image       = Colwyn Bay Community Hospital (geograph 3286184).jpg\n| Caption     = Colwyn Bay Community Hospital\n| map_type    = Wales Conwy\n| map_caption = Shown in Conwy County Borough\n| Logo        = <!-- optional -->\n| Location    = [[Colwyn Bay]]\n| Region      = Conwy County Borough\n| State       = Wales\n| Country     = UK\n| Coordinates = {{coord|53.2879|-3.7104|display=inline,title}}\n| HealthCare  = NHS\n| Type        = Community hospital\n| Speciality  = <!-- if devoted to a speciality, i.e. not if has broad spectrum of specialities -->\n| Standards   = <!-- optional if no national standards -->\n| Emergency   = \n| Affiliation =\n| Beds        =\n| Staff       = \n| Founded     = 1899\n| Closed      = \n| Website     = \n| Wiki-Links  = <!-- optional -->\n|}}\n'''Colwyn Bay Community Hospital''' ({{lang-cy|Ysbyty Cymuned Bae Colwyn}}) is a [[community hospital]] in [[Colwyn Bay]], Wales. It is managed by the [[Betsi Cadwaladr University Health Board]].\n\n==History==\nThe hospital has its origins in the Colwyn Bay Jubilee Cottage Hospital which was established in 1899.<ref name=na>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/hospitalrecords/details.asp?id=913|title=Colwyn Bay Community Hospital, Colwyn Bay|publisher=National Archives|accessdate=26 February 2019}}</ref> The present hospital, which was designed by Sidney Colwyn Foulkes and incorporated the latest concepts from the United States, opened as the Colwyn Bay and West Denbighshire Hospital in 1925.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://colwynbayheritage.org.uk/sidney-colwyn-foulkes/|title=Sidney Colwyn Foulkes|publisher=Colwyn Bay Heritage|accessdate=26 February 2019}}</ref> It joined the [[National Health Service]] in 1948 and became a community hospital in the 1980s.<ref name=na/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Hospitals established in 1899]]\n[[Category:Hospitals in Conwy County Borough]]\n[[Category:Hospital buildings completed in 1925]]\n[[Category:1899 establishments in Wales]]\n[[Category:NHS hospitals in Wales]]\n[[Category:Betsi Cadwaladr University Health Board]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Colwyn_Bay_Community_Hospital"}
{"title_page": "Ssese Islands", "text_new": "[[File:Kalangala District in Uganda.svg|thumb|right|Location of the Ssese Islands in Uganda]]\n\nThe '''Ssese Islands''' are an [[archipelago]] of eighty-four [[island]]s in the northwestern part of [[Lake Victoria]] in [[Uganda]]. The islands are coterminous with the [[Kalangala District]] in southern [[Central Region, Uganda|Central Uganda]], which does not have any territory on mainland Uganda.\n\n==Location==\nThe islands occupy the northwestern corner of [[Lake Victoria]], the second-largest freshwater lake in the world. The largest island in the archipelago is called [[Bugala Island]]. Its largest town, called [[Kalangala]] serves as the headquarters of the district that carries the same name ([[Kalangala District]]). Kalangala is located approximately {{convert|51|km|mi}}, across water, southwest of [[Entebbe]], in [[Wakiso District]], on the Ugandan mainland.<ref>[http://distancecalculator.globefeed.com/Uganda_Distance_Result.asp?fromplace=Entebbe%20Bay%20(Western%20Province)&toplace=Kalangala%20(Kalangala)&fromlat=0.0666667&tolat=-0.3088889&fromlng=32.4833333&tolng=32.225 Estimated Nautical Distance Between Entebbe And Kalangala With Map]</ref> The coordinates of the district are:0\u00b0 26' 0.00\"S, 32\u00b0 15' 0.00\"E (Latitude:-0.4333; Longitude:32.2500).\n\nThe islands lie in two main groups. The south west can be referred to as the '''Bugala Group''', after [[Bugala Island]], the largest in the archipelago. The northeastern group can be referred to as the '''Koome Group''', after [[Koome Island]], the largest in that group. The two groups are separated by the '''Koome Channel'''.\n\nOther islands in the Bugala Group include: [[Bubeke]], [[Bubembe Island|Bubembe]], [[Bufumira]], [[Bugaba Island|Bugaba]], [[Bukasa]], [[Buyova]], [[Funve]] and [[Serinya Island|Serinya]].  The main islands in the Koome Group include: [[Damba Island|Damba]], [[Koome]] and [[Luwaji]].\n\n==Overview==\nThe Sesse Islands are inhabited by the [[Bantu languages|Bantu]] speaking [[Bassese]] tribe, closely related to the [[Baganda]] and the [[Basoga]], and speaking a similar, though distinct language. Prior to the arrival of Europeans, the islands were one of the most important spiritual centers of the region. About 43 (50%) of the islands are inhabited. The islands vary in size from less than {{convert|10000|m2|acre}}, to over {{convert|40|km|mi}} in length for the largest island, [[Bugala Island]].\n\n[[Henry Morton Stanley]] described the inhabitants as \"the principal canoe builders and the greater number of the sailors of [[Muteesa I of Buganda|Mtesa's]] empire.\"<ref name=Stanley>Stanley, H.M., 1899, Through the Dark Continent, London: G. Newnes, {{ISBN|0486256677}}</ref>{{rp|168}}\n\n==Getting there==\nThe most popular route that the islands can be accessed is through Nakiwogo near Entebbe by MV Kalangala as the main gateway to the archipelagos. Transfer between Nakiwogo and Bugala Island is usually 3\u00bd hours.\n\nFrom Bukakata: From the western part of Uganda, a free car ferry links Bukakata mainland located 36&nbsp;km east of Masaka with Luku on Bugala Islands about 50 minutes sailing. The ferry sails either directions every few hours from early morning to late afternoon. The morning trips on Sunday are not available.\n\nFrom Kasenyi landing site: To get to Banda Island, there are small wooden boats departing from Kasenyi, a fishing village 7&nbsp;km off Entebbe-Kampala road; turn off is  5&nbsp;km outside Entebbe.\n\nOn Bugala island there are shared taxis that run from Kalangala to Luku.\n\n==Economic activity==\nThe principal [[industry]] in the Ssese Islands is [[fishing]] for the huge [[Nile Perch]], with much of the catch being exported. Overfishing is a huge concern on these and other islands in Lake Victoria. Other industries include [[agriculture]], [[forestry]] and [[tourism]].\n\n[[Livestock|Livestock farming]] is practiced on the islands. It is estimated that 3,000 [[cattle]], 250,000 [[poultry]] ([[chicken]] and [[ducks]]), 1,235 [[goat]]s and 7,000 [[pig]]s are kept on the islands.<ref>[http://www.ugandatravelguide.com/kalangala-sseseisland.html The Economy of Kalangala District]</ref>\n\nBIDCO, a private [[palm oil]] processor based in [[Jinja District]], on the mainland, owns a {{convert|15000|acre|ha}} palm oil [[plantation]] on the islands. In addition, outgrower farmers grow palm oil on contract with BIDCO and sell their produce to the processor.<ref>[http://www.bidco-oil.com/regional/index.php?conid=2 BIDCO Invests US$130 million in Uganda] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100404003219/http://www.bidco-oil.com/regional/index.php?conid=2 |date=2010-04-04 }}</ref> In 2010, the palm oil plant began generating 1.5MW of electricity through the burning of [[bagasse]] and some of the oil. The power supplies the oil processing plant and the excess is sold to [[Kalangala]], the largest town on the islands.<ref>[http://www.newvision.co.ug/D/8/220/710786/Bugala%20Island Overview of the BIDCO Palm Oil Project]</ref>\n\n[[Logging]] is another economic activity that is practiced on the Ssese Islands.\n\n==Flora and fauna==\nThe islands are also home to a variety of animals including [[primate]]s, which are not easily accessible on the mainland. This has led to the evolution of a nascent but growing tourism industry on the islands. Infrastructure is still rudimentary but is slowly improving.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Kalangala District]]\n* [[Koome Island]]\n* [[Bugala Island]]\n* [[Bugala Power Station]]\n* [[Kalangala]]\n* [[Central Region, Uganda]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{wikivoyage-inline|Ssese Islands}}\n* [https://www.miremberesort.co.ug Mirembe Resort Beach Hotel in Kalangala]\n* [https://maps.google.com/maps?q=00+26S,+32+15E&hl=en&ll=-0.34744,32.297058&spn=0.199123,0.748444&sll=0.274657,32.428894&sspn=0.796493,2.993774&t=p&z=11 Location of Ssese Islands At Google Maps]\n{{coord|00|26|00|S|32|15|00|E|region:UG_source:enwiki-uniquenames|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Kalangala District]]\n[[Category:Lake islands of Uganda]]\n[[Category:Islands of Lake Victoria]]\n[[Category:Central Region, Uganda]]\n[[Category:Palm oil production in Uganda]]\n[[Victoria Basin forest-savanna mosaic]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Kalangala District in Uganda.svg|thumb|right|Location of the Ssese Islands in Uganda]]\n\nThe '''Ssese Islands''' are an [[archipelago]] of eighty-four [[island]]s in the northwestern part of [[Lake Victoria]] in [[Uganda]]. The islands are coterminous with the [[Kalangala District]] in southern [[Central Region, Uganda|Central Uganda]], which does not have any territory on mainland Uganda.\n\n==Location==\nThe islands occupy the northwestern corner of [[Lake Victoria]], the second-largest freshwater lake in the world. The largest island in the archipelago is called [[Bugala Island]]. Its largest town, called [[Kalangala]] serves as the headquarters of the district that carries the same name ([[Kalangala District]]). Kalangala is located approximately {{convert|51|km|mi}}, across water, southwest of [[Entebbe]], in [[Wakiso District]], on the Ugandan mainland.<ref>[http://distancecalculator.globefeed.com/Uganda_Distance_Result.asp?fromplace=Entebbe%20Bay%20(Western%20Province)&toplace=Kalangala%20(Kalangala)&fromlat=0.0666667&tolat=-0.3088889&fromlng=32.4833333&tolng=32.225 Estimated Nautical Distance Between Entebbe And Kalangala With Map]</ref> The coordinates of the district are:0\u00b0 26' 0.00\"S, 32\u00b0 15' 0.00\"E (Latitude:-0.4333; Longitude:32.2500).\n\nThe islands lie in two main groups. The south west can be referred to as the '''Bugala Group''', after [[Bugala Island]], the largest in the archipelago. The northeastern group can be referred to as the '''Koome Group''', after [[Koome Island]], the largest in that group. The two groups are separated by the '''Koome Channel'''.\n\nOther islands in the Bugala Group include: [[Bubeke]], [[Bubembe Island|Bubembe]], [[Bufumira]], [[Bugaba Island|Bugaba]], [[Bukasa]], [[Buyova]], [[Funve]] and [[Serinya Island|Serinya]].  The main islands in the Koome Group include: [[Damba Island|Damba]], [[Koome]] and [[Luwaji]].\n\n==Overview==\nThe Sesse Islands are inhabited by the [[Bantu languages|Bantu]] speaking [[Bassese]] tribe, closely related to the [[Baganda]] and the [[Basoga]], and speaking a similar, though distinct language. Prior to the arrival of [[Europeans]], the islands were one of the most important spiritual centers of the region. About 43 (50%) of the islands are inhabited. The islands vary in size from less than {{convert|10000|m2|acre}}, to over {{convert|40|km|mi}} in length for the largest island, [[Bugala Island]].\n\n[[Henry Morton Stanley]] described the inhabitants as \"the principal canoe builders and the greater number of the sailors of [[Muteesa I of Buganda|Mtesa's]] empire.\"<ref name=Stanley>Stanley, H.M., 1899, Through the Dark Continent, London: G. Newnes, {{ISBN|0486256677}}</ref>{{rp|168}}\n\n==Getting there==\nThe most popular route that the islands can be accessed is through Nakiwogo near Entebbe by MV Kalangala as the main gateway to the archipelagos. Transfer between Nakiwogo and Bugala Island is usually 3\u00bd hours.\n\nFrom Bukakata: From the western part of Uganda, a free car ferry links Bukakata mainland located 36&nbsp;km east of Masaka with Luku on Bugala Islands about 50 minutes sailing. The ferry sails either directions every few hours from early morning to late afternoon. The morning trips on Sunday are not available.\n\nFrom Kasenyi landing site: To get to Banda Island, there are small wooden boats departing from Kasenyi, a fishing village 7&nbsp;km off Entebbe-Kampala road; turn off is  5&nbsp;km outside Entebbe.\n\nOn Bugala island there are shared taxis that run from Kalangala to Luku.\n\n==Economic activity==\nThe principal [[industry]] in the Ssese Islands is [[fishing]] for the huge [[Nile Perch]], with much of the catch being exported. Overfishing is a huge concern on these and other islands in Lake Victoria. Other industries include [[agriculture]], [[forestry]] and [[tourism]].\n\n[[Livestock|Livestock farming]] is practiced on the islands. It is estimated that 3,000 [[cattle]], 250,000 [[poultry]] ([[chicken]] and [[ducks]]), 1,235 [[goat]]s and 7,000 [[pig]]s are kept on the islands.<ref>[http://www.ugandatravelguide.com/kalangala-sseseisland.html The Economy of Kalangala District]</ref>\n\nBIDCO, a private [[palm oil]] processor based in [[Jinja District]], on the mainland, owns a {{convert|15000|acre|ha}} palm oil [[plantation]] on the islands. In addition, outgrower farmers grow palm oil on contract with BIDCO and sell their produce to the processor.<ref>[http://www.bidco-oil.com/regional/index.php?conid=2 BIDCO Invests US$130 million in Uganda] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100404003219/http://www.bidco-oil.com/regional/index.php?conid=2 |date=2010-04-04 }}</ref> In 2010, the palm oil plant began generating 1.5MW of electricity through the burning of [[bagasse]] and some of the oil. The power supplies the oil processing plant and the excess is sold to [[Kalangala]], the largest town on the islands.<ref>[http://www.newvision.co.ug/D/8/220/710786/Bugala%20Island Overview of the BIDCO Palm Oil Project]</ref>\n\n[[Logging]] is another economic activity that is practiced on the Ssese Islands.\n\n==Flora and fauna==\nThe islands are also home to a variety of animals including [[primate]]s, which are not easily accessible on the mainland. This has led to the evolution of a nascent but growing tourism industry on the islands. Infrastructure is still rudimentary but is slowly improving.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Kalangala District]]\n* [[Koome Island]]\n* [[Bugala Island]]\n* [[Bugala Power Station]]\n* [[Kalangala]]\n* [[Central Region, Uganda]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{wikivoyage-inline|Ssese Islands}}\n* [https://www.mirembe