o|title=The Complete New Zealand Music Charts 1966-2006|publisher=RIANZ|year=2007|isbn=978-1-877443-00-8}}</ref>}}\n{{certification Table Entry|type=album|region=Sweden|artist=Mariah Carey|title=Emotions|award=Platinum|certyear=1992|relyear=1991|accessdate=August 31, 2017}}\n{{certification Table Entry|type=album|region=Switzerland|artist=Mariah Carey|title=Emotions|award=Gold|certyear=1994|relyear=1991|accessdate=August 31, 2017}}\n{{certification Table Entry|type=album|region=United Kingdom|artist=Mariah Carey|title=Emotions|award=Platinum|certyear=1992|relyear=1991|accessdate=August 31, 2017}}\n{{certification Table Entry|type=album|region=United States|artist=Mariah Carey|title=Emotions|award=Platinum|number=4|certyear=1994|relyear=1991|accessdate=August 31, 2017|salesamount=3,595,000|salesref=<ref name=\"ussales\"/>}}\n{{Certification Table Summary}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Worldwide|salesamount=13,000,000|salesref=<ref name=\"https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=UHSNRIlMFMM\"/>|nocert=yes}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n'''Works cited '''\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{Cite book\n | ref = harv\n | last = Nickson\n | first = Chris\n | title = Mariah Carey revisited: her story\n | year = 1998\n | publisher = [[St. Martin's Press]]\n | isbn = 978-0-312-19512-0\n }}\n* {{Cite book\n | ref = harv\n | last = Shapiro\n | first = Marc\n | title = Mariah Carey: The Unauthorized Biography\n | publisher = [[ECW Press]]\n | year = 2001\n | isbn = 978-1-55022-444-3\n }}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{Mariah Carey}}\n\n[[Category:Mariah Carey albums]]\n[[Category:1991 albums]]\n[[Category:Columbia Records albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Walter Afanasieff]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by David Cole (record producer)]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Carole King]]\n[[Category:Albums involved in plagiarism controversies]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1991 studio album by Mariah Carey}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2017}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name         = Emotions\n| type         = studio\n| artist       = [[Mariah Carey]]\n| cover        = Emotions Mariah Carey.png\n| alt          = A brunette woman in a white dress standing in front of a dark desert like background, the words \"MARIAH CAREY\" are on the left hand side of the artwork with the words \"EMOTIONS\" are towards the bottom right hand side of the artwork.\n| released     = September 17, 1991\n| recorded     = 1991\n| venue        = \n| studio       = {{flatlist|\n*Skywalker Sound <br>{{small|([[Marin County, California]])}}\n*[[The Plant Recording Studios]]<br>{{small|([[Sausalito, California]])}}\n*[[Right Track Recording]]\n*Axis Studios\n*Skyline Studios\n*Battery Studios\n*Electric Lady Studios\n*Giant Recording Studios<br>{{small|([[New York City, New York]])}}}}\n| genre        = * [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]<ref name=\"Qmag\"/>\n| length       = 47:01\n| label        = [[Columbia Records|Columbia]]\n| producer     = {{flatlist|\n*[[Tommy Mottola]] {{small|([[Executive producer#Music|exec.]])}}\n*[[Mariah Carey]]\n*[[Walter Afanasieff]]\n*[[David Cole (producer)|David Cole]]\n*[[Robert Clivill\u00e9s]]}}\n| prev_title   = [[Mariah Carey (album)|Mariah Carey]]\n| prev_year    = 1990\n| next_title   = [[MTV Unplugged (Mariah Carey EP)|MTV Unplugged]]\n| next_year    = 1992\n| misc         = {{Singles\n | name        = Emotions\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Emotions (Mariah Carey song)|Emotions]]\n | single1date = August 13, 1991\n | single2     = [[Can't Let Go (Mariah Carey song)|Can't Let Go]]\n | single2date = October 23, 1991\n | single3     = [[Make It Happen (Mariah Carey song)|Make It Happen]]\n | single3date = April 4, 1992\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Emotions''''' is the second studio album by American singer and songwriter [[Mariah Carey]]. It was released on September 17, 1991 by [[Columbia Records]]. The album deviated from the formula of Carey's [[Mariah Carey (album)|1990 self-titled debut album]], as she had more creative control over the material she produced and recorded. Additionally, ''Emotions'' features influences from a range of genres such as [[gospel music|gospel]], [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]], [[Soul music|soul]] and 1950s, 1960s and 1970s balladry infusion. On the record, Carey worked with a variety of producers and writers, including [[Walter Afanasieff]], the only hold over from her previous effort. Additionally, Carey wrote and produced the album's material with [[Robert Clivill\u00e9s]] and [[David Cole (producer)|David Cole]] from [[C+C Music Factory]] and [[Carole King]], with whom she wrote one song.\n\nUpon release, ''Emotions'' received generally mixed reviews from contemporary music critics. The album debuted at number four on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], surprising many critics following the success of Carey's debut, which spent eleven weeks atop the chart. While selling far less than ''Mariah Carey'', ''Emotions'' was eventually certified quadruple-[[RIAA certification|Platinum]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA), denoting shipments of four million copies throughout the country, with estimated sales standing at 3,595,000 copies. ''Emotions'' achieved moderate success outside the United States, peaking within the top ten in Australia, Canada, the Netherlands, New Zealand, Norway and the United Kingdom. Its success in Japan was strong, shipping one million copies there. The album has sold 8 million copies worldwide. <!--- Do not change the global sales figure without adding a reliable source --->\n\nThree commercial singles were released from the album. [[Emotions (Mariah Carey song)|The title track]], the album's lead single, became Carey's fifth chart topper on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], making her the only artist in history to have their first five singles reach the chart's summit. Additionally, it became Carey's third chart topper in Canada, and reached the top ten in France, the Netherlands and New Zealand. \"[[Can't Let Go (Mariah Carey song)|Can't Let Go]]\" was released as the second single from ''Emotions'' on October 23, 1991. Due to Columbia's removal of the single from stores in an attempt to boost the album's sales, \"Can't Let Go\" failed to become her sixth chart topper in the US, peaking at number two. European and worldwide success was very limited, reaching the top 20 in only Canada and the UK. Similarly, \"[[Make It Happen (Mariah Carey song)|Make It Happen]]\" peaked at number five in the US, and achieved relatively weak international charting, prompting Columbia to halt promotion of the album.\n\n== Background ==\nFollowing the success of Carey's [[Mariah Carey (album)|self-titled]] debut album, critics wondered whether or not she would tour in order to promote the album in the major worldwide music markets.<ref name=\"Nickson\">{{harvnb|Nickson|2001|p=50}}</ref> However, Carey expressed in several interviews that due to the strenuous nature and the sheer difficulty of her songs, she feared a tour with back-to-back shows would not be possible, aside from the long travel times and constant travel.<ref name=\"Nickson\"/> With the extra time, Carey began writing and producing material for ''Emotions'' around the same time that her debut's third single, \"[[Someday (Mariah Carey song)|Someday]],\" was released in December 1990. During this time period in music, it was traditional for an artist to release a [[studio album]] every two years in their prime, allowing the singles to fully promote the album through airwaves, as well as television appearances.<ref name=\"Nickson2\">{{harvnb|Nickson|2001|p=51}}</ref> Additionally, after a tour that would usually follow, as the next album would be released and would gain new fans, they would search the artist's catalog, and purchase the previous album in hopes of learning of their older work.<ref name=\"Nickson2\"/> [[Sony Music Entertainment|Sony]], however, chose to market Carey in a different fashion, leaning towards the traditional form in the 1960s, where acts would release an LP every year.<ref name=\"Nickson3\">{{harvnb|Nickson|2001|p=52}}</ref> They felt that Carey's reputation of being a \"studio worm\" and a songwriter from a young age would be captivating enough to deliver a new album more often than most.<ref name=\"Nickson3\"/>\n\nAs writing for the album came under way, Carey had a falling out with [[Ben Margulies]], the man whom Carey had written seven of the eleven songs on Carey's debut with.<ref name=\"Nickson3\"/> Together, the duo had written and produced seven songs for Carey's demo tape which she handed to [[Tommy Mottola]]. Their parting of ways was due to a contract Carey had signed prior to her signing with [[Columbia Records|Columbia]].<ref name=\"Nickson3\"/> Carey had agreed to split not only the songwriting royalties from the songs, but half of her earnings as well, something she never thought twice about while writing songs in his father's basement.<ref name=\"Nickson3\"/> However, when the time came to write music for ''Emotions'', Sony officials made it clear he would only be paid the fair amount given to co-writers on an album.<ref name=\"Nickson3\"/> Following the discussion, Margulies filed a lawsuit against Sony, claiming that under contract, he would be entitled to work with Carey, as well as reap extra benefits. After an almost one year lawsuit, the judge settled that Margulies was to earn ten percent of Carey's direct earnings from her record sales, not including an income from any other ventures.<ref name=\"Nickson3\"/> While settled, their relationship remained ruined, damaged by what Carey considered treachery. In an interview with [[Fred Bronson]], Carey said the following regarding the contract: \"I signed blindly. Later, I tried to make it right so we could continue...but he wouldn't accept it.\"<ref name=\"Nickson3\"/> After the settlement, Margulies spoke of his feelings on the matter, claiming he would hope to one day write again with Carey, placing most of the blame on the record label and concluding \"Hopefully one day, art will prevail over business.\"<ref name=\"Nickson3\"/>\n\n== Recording ==\n''Mariah Carey'' had originally been recorded in Margulies' father's basement, with old and minimal equipment. After being signed to Columbia, the songs that would be used for the album were re-mastered and re-recorded in professional studios.<ref name=\"Nickson4\">{{harvnb|Nickson|2001|p=53}}</ref> However, due to Sony's involvement in the project, they did not allow Carey to produce most of the album, hoping the aid of several famed record producers would be able to ensure Carey's already deemed \"exquisite\" songs would become popular. After the album's success however, Carey was allowed more freedom on ''Emotions'' than on her debut.<ref name=\"Nickson4\"/> Since she no longer had a working or personal relationship with Margulies, she chose to work with mostly different musicians than those of her previous effort, with the exception of [[Walter Afanasieff]], the only hold over from ''Mariah Carey''.<ref name=\"Nickson4\"/> Even though he had only co-written \"[[Love Takes Time]],\" and had only produced part of the album, Carey felt a strong working chemistry with him, soon developing a unique form of songwriting alongside him. Aside from Afanasieff, Carey worked with [[Robert Clivill\u00e9s]] and [[David Cole (producer)|David Cole]] from the dance-music influenced production duo, [[C+C Music Factory]].<ref name=\"Nickson4\"/> Working with the duo was originally Mottola's suggestion, but after meeting the pair, Carey agreed and wrote four songs together with them.<ref name=\"Nickson4\"/>\n\nAdditionally, aside from the three men, Carey worked with [[Carole King]], a female [[singer-songwriter]] who had been predominantly popular in the 1970s.<ref name=\"Nickson5\">{{harvnb|Nickson|2001|p=54}}</ref> However, unlike with C+C Music Factory, King approached Carey, hoping to work with her after hearing her perform live on ''[[The Arsenio Hall Show]]''. During a conversation with Carey, King suggested that she cover \"[[(You Make Me Feel Like) A Natural Woman]],\" a song she had written with [[Gerry Goffin]] for [[Aretha Franklin]].<ref name=\"Nickson5\"/> After giving it some thought, Carey declined the offer, feeling uncomfortable about recording a song she felt one of her musical influences performed so perfectly.<ref name=\"Nickson5\"/> Still determined on working with Carey, King flew to New York for one day, to try to create a ballad of some sort.<ref name=\"Nickson5\"/> The two ladies sat together by a piano over the course of the day, and by nightfall, had written and arranged a song titled \"[[If It's Over]].\"<ref name=\"Nickson6\">{{harvnb|Nickson|2001|p=55}}</ref> After working with Carey, King said in an interview \"I love her voice. She's very expressive. She gives a lot of meaning to what she sings.\"<ref name=\"Nickson6\"/> After recording \"If It's Over,\" Carey expressed the musical connection she shared with Afanasieff, as well as the creative format in which she wrote and produced her music when with him, or working with C+C Music Factory.<ref name=\"Nickson7\">{{harvnb|Nickson|2001|p=56}}</ref> When working with Afanasieff, the duo would sit by a piano, and lead each other vocally and musically, until they would reach the right note and arrangement. During an interview in 1992, Afanasieff described how Carey would stand next to him, and begin singing different notes and tunes she was thinking of, while he would follow her with the piano.<ref name=\"Nickson7\"/> In doing so, he would help lead her to the right note and vice versa. Carey described their working relationship as \"very unique,\" and felt it to be very similar to the form in which she had worked with Margulies.<ref name=\"Nickson7\"/> While similar, Carey's creative process with Cole and Clivill\u00e9s proved different; they would bring her several different tapes and tunes, of which she would choose from. Afterwards, they would work on building the already created melody, and have Carey add and build onto it, as well as writing the lyrics and [[Key (music)|key]].<ref name=\"Nickson7\"/>\n\n== Music and lyrics ==\n{{listen\n | filename     = Mariah Carey - Can't Let Go (1992).ogg\n | title        = \"Can't Let Go\"\n | description  = A sample from the song's chorus. It features Carey's lower registers an husky vocals, as well as its minimal production.\n | format       = [[Ogg]]\n\n | filename2     = 05 If It's Over.ogg\n | title2        = \"If It's Over\"\n | description2  = A sample of the song's bridge. It features Carey's upper registers as well as the song's gospel influence.\n | format2       = [[Ogg]]\n}}\nUnlike Carey's debut album, which featured a more contemporary [[Pop music|pop]] and [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] background, ''Emotions'' proved to be far different. It borrowed from several genres ranging from gospel, [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]], [[Soul music|soul]], pop and 1960s and 1970s influences.{{Citation needed|date=June 2016}} The album's lead single \"[[Emotions (Mariah Carey song)|Emotions]]\" borrowed heavily from 1970s disco, and flaunted Carey's [[Vocal range|upper range]] and extensive use of the [[whistle register]].<ref name=\"Nickson8\">{{harvnb|Nickson|2001|p=60}}</ref> The song's lyrics were described as \"joyful\" by author Chris Nickson, and told of a strong and deep emotion felt by the protagonist when with their lover.<ref name=\"Nickson8\"/> One of the album's more gospel infused songs, \"And You Don't Remember,\" featured organ [[Chord progression|chord changes]] and held minimal production in order to give the [[Singing|vocals]] a more \"raw and sixties feel.\"<ref name=\"Nickson8\"/> It and the former song were part of a trio of tracks from the album that were meant to pay homage to [[Motown]] [[ballad]]s, with the inclusion of soft church [[choir]] vocals, and sole [[Arrangement|musical arrangement]] by Carey.<ref name=\"Nickson8\"/> Its [[lyrics]] reflected the song's raw chorus, telling of girl that is promised the world by her boyfriend, and quickly forget about her and moves to the next one. After the heartbreak, the protagonist asks him \"Don't You Remember\" all those things he had promised her, and the things they had spoken and dreamed about doing together.<ref name=\"Nickson8\"/> \"[[Can't Let Go (Mariah Carey song)|Can't Let Go]],\" the album's second single, is a slow ballad, featuring sad and yearning lyrical content.<ref name=\"Nickson9\">{{harvnb|Nickson|2001|p=61}}</ref> The song's introduction featured minor chord changes, and drew influence from [[1950s in music|fifties balladry]].<ref name=\"Nickson9\"/> For the duration of the first half of the song, Carey sings in her lower and huskier registers, eventually leading to the [[Belt (music)|belted]] crescendo and [[falsetto]] and whistle finish.<ref name=\"Nickson9\"/> Of the ten tracks on the album, Carey felt her most autobiographical lyrics were featured on \"[[Make It Happen (Mariah Carey song)|Make It Happen]],\" which told of Carey's poor and difficult teen life prior to being signed by Columbia.<ref name=\"Nickson9\"/> It continues telling of the importance of faith and prayer to God. Nickson described its instrumentation as \"restrained\" and \"very Motownish,\" as well as noting its soft gospel infusion.<ref name=\"Nickson9\"/> Critically, the most anticipated song on the album was \"[[If It's Over]],\" Carey's collaboration with King. It was influenced by sixties and seventies gospel and other soulful genres.<ref name=\"Nickson10\">{{harvnb|Nickson|2001|p=62}}</ref> According to Nickson, the song's instrumentation and basis was crucial to Carey's performance throughout the song. Additionally, he described its content and instrumentation:\n<blockquote>\nAs a song full of gospel and soulful influences, it allowed Mariah to really tear loose and show what she could do \u2013 which in reality was far more than the vocal gymnastics that seemed to comprise her reputation so far. From a deep rumble to a high wail, she covered five octaves wonderfully, as the power of the tune built. The backing vocals \u2013 which once again had those churchy harmonies \u2013 filled out the spare melody, as did the stately horns, which entered towards the end. The song was truly a vocal showcase for Mariah.<ref name=\"Nickson10\"/>\n</blockquote>\nThe next song on the album's track list, \"You're So Cold,\" was originally intended to be the lead single from ''Emotions'', eventually being switched for the title track. The song's introduction features a [[piano]] and [[a cappella|a capella]] vocal, working into its chorus.<ref name=\"Nickson10\"/> Chris Nickson wrote \"The song sailed into the chorus, driven by the house-y piano work, the bubbly, snacking rhythm belying the angry lyrics, the upbeat tone of voice.\"<ref name=\"Nickson10\"/> As Nickson hinted at, its lyrics featured an angry message, calling out an unfaithful lover and asking how he could be \"So Cold.\" \"So Blessed\" was a song Carey wrote with Afanasieff, infusing fifties style pop balladry into it. Carey's voice in the song is very restrained, as she stays within her lower registers throughout the duration of the track.<ref name=\"Nickson10\"/> \"To Be Around You\" was described by Nickson as \"far more [[staccato]].\" Its production and melody was intended to pay tribute to \"[[Got to Be Real]]\" by [[Cheryl Lynn]], as well as featuring spoken voices towards the end of the song.<ref name=\"Nickson10\"/> Nickson described \"Till the End of Time\" as a \"gentle, almost lullaby melody.\"<ref name=\"Nickson11\">{{harvnb|Nickson|2001|p=63}}</ref> It was a love ballad, preparing the listener for the song's final track, \"The Wind.\" The latter song featured the album's strongest [[jazz]] influence, and sampled a piano melody from [[Russ Freeman (pianist)|Russell Freeman]] during the 1950s.<ref name=\"Nickson11\"/> After Afanasieff presented Carey with the melody he had discovered, it inspired her to write the [[melody]] and lyrics, which told of a friend that perished in a drunk-driving accident.<ref name=\"Nickson11\"/> Musically, the album fulfilled its greatest challenge, according to critics. It had helped master Carey's usage and infusion of several genres which she had not tapped into during the recording of her debut.<ref name=\"Nickson11\"/>\n\n== Promotion ==\nAs with ''Mariah Carey'' the previous year, Carey did not embark on a tour to promote the album, due to the long travel times and strenuous schedules on her voice.<ref name=\"shapiro\">{{harvnb|Shapiro|2001|p=60}}</ref> However, while not touring the world, Carey promoted ''Emotions'' through an array of television and award show appearances, stateside and across Europe.<ref name=\"shapiro\"/> Carey performed \"[[Emotions (Mariah Carey song)|Emotions]]\" live for the first time at the 1991 [[MTV Video Music Award]]s, backed by several male and female back up vocalists.<ref name=\"shapiro\"/> Following the award show appearance, she sang \"Emotions\" on ''[[The Arsenio Hall Show]]'', airing on September 23, 1991. Additionally, Carey performed the song at the [[1992 Soul Train Music Awards]], and on British music program and talk show ''[[Top of the Pops]]'' and ''[[Des O'Connor]]''.<ref name=\"shapiro2\">{{harvnb|Shapiro|2001|p=62}}</ref> Additional European stops included ''Sondagstoppet'' and ''Kulan'' in Sweden during mid-September 1991. All of the above-mentioned performances included \"[[Can't Let Go (Mariah Carey song)|Can't Let Go]]\" as a secondary performance in the night.<ref name=\"shapiro2\"/> \"Can't Let Go\" was sung on additional programs such as ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'', a pre-filmed studio clip on ''[[Today (NBC program)|The Today Show]]''. While the album's final single \"[[Make It Happen (Mariah Carey song)|Make It Happen]]\" was released only months after ''Emotions'' release, the song was not performed during the album's original chart run, however making its way onto the set-list of several of Carey following tours.<ref name=\"shapiro2\"/> On February 26, 1992, Carey performed \"[[If It's Over]]\" at the [[34th Grammy Awards|34th annual]] [[Grammy Award]], with a full orchestra and several back up singers.<ref name=\"shapiro\"/>\n\n=== Singles ===\n{{listen\n | filename     = Mariah Carry - Emotions.ogg\n | title        = \"Emotions\"\n | description  = A sample from the song's final chorus, featuring Carey's usage of the whistle register.\n | format       = [[Ogg]]\n}}\nThree commercial singles were released from ''Emotions''. The album's lead single of [[Emotions (Mariah Carey song)|the same name]] became Carey's fifth chart topper in the United States, making her the only act in history to have their first five singles reach the charts summit in the country.<ref name=lamb/><ref name=\"Billboard Hot 100\">{{cite web|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=mariah carey|chart=all}}|title=Billboard \u2013 Artists \u2013 Mariah Carey|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|accessdate=August 14, 2010}}</ref> Additionally, \"[[Emotions (Mariah Carey song)|Emotions]]\" topped the singles chart in Canada, reached the top five in New Zealand, and peaked within the top twenty in Australia, the Netherlands and the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.1666&type=1&interval=50&PHPSESSID=4dp17sl7hp9qmhhj3vmcenr836|title=Top Singles \u2013 Volume 54, No. 22, November 02 1991|magazine=[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]|date=November 2, 1991|accessdate=September 13, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121018133359/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.1666&type=1&interval=50&PHPSESSID=4dp17sl7hp9qmhhj3vmcenr836|archive-date=October 18, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://charts.nz/showitem.asp?interpret=Mariah+Carey&titel=Emotions&cat=s|title=Mariah Carey \u2013 Emotions|work=New Zealand Singles Chart|publisher=Hung Medien|accessdate=March 20, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Mariah+Carey&titel=Emotions&cat=s|title=Mariah Carey \u2013 Emotions|work=ARIA Charts|publisher=Hung Medien|accessdate=March 20, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://dutchcharts.nl/showitem.asp?interpret=Mariah+Carey&titel=Emotions&cat=s|title=Mariah Carey \u2013 Emotions|work=Dutch Top 40|publisher=Hung Medien|accessdate=March 20, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AcxNW8eP?url=http://dutchcharts.nl/showitem.asp?interpret=Mariah+Carey&titel=Emotions&cat=s|archivedate=September 12, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theofficialcharts.com/archive-chart/_/1/1991-11-09/|title=Top 40 Official UK Singles Archive|work=The Official Charts Company|publisher=British Phonographic Industry|date=November 9, 1991|accessdate=November 28, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AcxOR3Ci?url=http://www.officialcharts.com/archive-chart/_/1/1991-11-09/|archivedate=September 12, 2012}}</ref> The song garnered positive critical response, with Bill Lamb from [[About.com]] rating it \"among her best.\"<ref name=lamb/> Steve Morse from ''The Boston Globe'' called Carey's high registers in the song a \"feeling of pure joy,\" whereas Jan DeKnock from the ''Chicago Tribune'' described Carey's voice as \"breathtaking.\"<ref name=deknock/><ref name=morse/> The song's music video features different scenes of Carey singing and enjoying herself throughout a car ride by the countryside, as well as a small celebration with several dancers.\n\nThe album's second release, \"[[Can't Let Go (Mariah Carey song)|Can't Let Go]],\" reached the number two position on the ''Billboard'' [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]], failing to top the chart due to [[Columbia Records|Columbia]]'s retraction of the single in order to boost sales of the album.<ref name=\"Billboard Hot 100\"/> Aside from Canada, where it attained a peak of number three, \"Can't Let Go\" performed weakly across continental Europe, reaching the top twenty in only the UK.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.2042&type=1&interval=50&PHPSESSID=4dp17sl7hp9qmhhj3vmcenr836|title=Top Singles \u2013 Volume 55, No. 6, February 01 1992|magazine=RPM|date=February 1, 1992|accessdate=September 13, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121018133531/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.2042&type=1&interval=50&PHPSESSID=4dp17sl7hp9qmhhj3vmcenr836|archive-date=October 18, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theofficialcharts.com/archive-chart/_/1/1992-02-01/|title=Top 40 Official UK Singles Archive|work=The Official Charts Company|publisher=British Phonographic Industry|date=February 1, 1992|accessdate=November 28, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AcxR4VGk?url=http://www.officialcharts.com/archive-chart/_/1/1992-02-01/|archivedate=September 12, 2012}}</ref> The song's corresponding video was filmed in black and white, and featured Carey's hair in a straightened style for the first time in her career. The video predominantly features close-up scenes of Carey by a small outdoor fountain, as well as blooming white roses. \"[[Make It Happen (Mariah Carey song)|Make It Happen]]\" was released as the third and final single from ''Emotions'' on April 4, 1992. It peaked at number five in the United States, and as \"Can't Let Go,\" charted weakly throughout Europe, coming in at number seven in Canada, seventeen in the UK, and thirty-five and forty-seven in Australia and the Netherlands, respectively.<ref name=\"Billboard Hot 100\"/><ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.2130&type=1&interval=50&PHPSESSID=4dp17sl7hp9qmhhj3vmcenr836|title=Top Singles \u2013 Volume 55, No. 20, May 16, 1992|magazine=RPM|date=May 16, 1992|accessdate=September 13, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121018133604/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.2130&type=1&interval=50&PHPSESSID=4dp17sl7hp9qmhhj3vmcenr836|archive-date=October 18, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theofficialcharts.com/archive-chart/_/1/1992-04-25/|title=Top 40 Official UK Singles Archive|work=The Official Charts Company|publisher=British Phonographic Industry|date=April 25, 1992|accessdate=November 28, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AcxSGsvz?url=http://www.officialcharts.com/archive-chart/_/1/1992-04-25/|archivedate=September 12, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Mariah+Carey&titel=Make+It+Happen&cat=s |title=Mariah Carey \u2013 Make It Happen |work=ARIA Charts |publisher=Hung Medien |accessdate=March 20, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100117041557/http://australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Mariah%2BCarey&titel=Make%2BIt%2BHappen&cat=s |archivedate=January 17, 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://dutchcharts.nl/showitem.asp?interpret=Mariah+Carey&titel=Make+It+Happen&cat=s |title=Mariah Carey \u2013 Make It Happen |work=Dutch Top 40 |publisher=Hung Medien |accessdate=March 20, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121025065417/http://dutchcharts.nl/showitem.asp?interpret=Mariah%2BCarey&titel=Make%2BIt%2BHappen&cat=s |archivedate=October 25, 2012 }}</ref> The song was praised by critics; Morse called it \"a clear slice of spiritual autobiography,\" and called the last chorus \"glorious.\"<ref name=morse/> Similarly, DeKnock called the song \"upbeat and inspirational.\"<ref name=deknock/> The video filmed for \"Make It Happen\" featured Carey performing in front of an audience in a large cathedral-like church, alongside back-up singers and child dancers. These three singles have been involved in plagiarism controversies and each disputes has been settled out of court<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/story/mariah-carey-accused-of-plagiarism|title=Mariah Carey Accused of Plagiarism|last=Friedman|first=Roger|date=2015-03-25|website=Fox News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-29}}</ref>.\n\n== Critical reception ==\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[About.com]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=lamb>{{cite web|url=http://top40.about.com/od/reviews/gr/mcemotion.htm|title=Mariah Carey 'Emotions'|last=Lamb|first=Bill|work=[[About.com]]|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|accessdate=March 19, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AcxKWqpN?url=http://top40.about.com/od/reviews/gr/mcemotion.htm|archivedate=September 12, 2012}}</ref>\n| rev2 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev2Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=erlewine/>\n| rev3 = ''[[Christgau's Consumer Guide]]''\n| rev3Score = {{Rating-Christgau|dud}}<ref name=\"CG\"/>\n| rev4 = ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''\n| rev4Score = {{Rating|3|4}}<ref name=deknock>{{cite web|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1991-09-26/features/9103130224_1_star-ballads-soulful|title=Mariah Carey Emotions|last=DeKnock|first=Jan|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|publisher=Tribune Company|date=September 29, 1991|accessdate=March 19, 2011}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[Encyclopedia of Popular Music]]''\n| rev5Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite book|last=Larkin|first=Colin|authorlink=Colin Larkin (writer)|year=2011|chapter=Mariah Carey|title=[[Encyclopedia of Popular Music]]|publisher=[[Omnibus Press]]|isbn=0857125958|edition=5th}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev6Score = C<ref name=berger/>\n| rev7 = ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''\n| rev7Score = {{Rating|2|4}}<ref name=hunt/>\n| rev8 = ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]''\n| rev8Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"Qmag\"/>\n| rev9 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev9Score = {{Rating|2|5}}<ref name=tannen/>\n| rev10 = ''[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide]]''\n| rev10Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"Berger\">{{cite book|last=Berger|first=Arion|chapter=Mariah Carey|pages=[https://archive.org/details/newrollingstonea00brac/page/138 138\u201339]|year=2004|editor1-last=Brackett|editor1-first=Nathan|editor2-last=Hoard|editor2-first=Christian|title=[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide]]|publisher=[[Simon and Schuster]]|isbn=0743201698}}</ref>\n}}\nIn a contemporary review, ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' critic Rob Tannenbaum found ''Emotions'' dependent on \"commercial dance-pop\" and Carey's indulgent vocal exercises, making it difficult for listeners to connect with the lyrics. \"Carey has a remarkable vocal gift, but to date, unfortunately, her singing has been far more impressive than expressive,\" Tannenbaum wrote.<ref name=tannen>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/emotions-19911114|title=Mariah Carey: Emotions|last=Tannenbaum|first=Rob|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|publisher=[[Jann Wenner|Wenner Media]]|date=November 14, 1991|accessdate=March 19, 2011}}</ref> Dennis Hunt from the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' said Carey's \"spectacular and impressive\" voice was comparable to that of [[Whitney Houston]], but criticized the songwriting and production for \"playing high on the angst scale.\"<ref name=hunt>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1991-09-15/entertainment/ca-3476_1_mariah-carey|title=Fall Album Special: Sappy Songs Underwhelm Carey's 'Emotions'|last=Hunt|first=Dennis|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|publisher=Tribune Company|date=September 15, 1991|accessdate=March 19, 2011}}</ref> In ''[[The New York Times]]'', [[Stephen Holden]] believed the record showcased Carey's vocal strengths more effectively than her debut, but showed no improvement in writing lyrics, which Holden said \"describe the rapturous highs and desperate lows of romance in blunt, strung-together pop clich\u00e9s, with minimal rhyming.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Holden|first=Stephen|authorlink=Stephen Holden|date=September 15, 1991|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/09/15/arts/pop-music-the-pop-gospel-according-to-mariah-carey.html?pagewanted=all|title=POP MUSIC; The Pop-Gospel According To Mariah Carey|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=September 16, 2016}}</ref> Arion Berger from ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' found the record \"colder and more calculated\" than Carey's debut, describing ''Emotions'' as \"the hybrid progeny of a venerable tradition \u2014 the tradition of the R&B diva \u2014 and crass commercial instincts. It's gospel without soul, love songs without passion, pop without buoyancy.\"<ref name=berger>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20272922,00.html|title=Mariah Carey \u2013 Emotions|last=Berger|first=Arion|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time Inc.|Time]]. [[Time Warner]]|date=October 11, 1991|accessdate=March 19, 2011}}</ref> ''[[Orlando Sentinel]]'' editor Parry Gettelman was also critical of Carey's vocal acrobatics, writing that the singer had become \"so enamored of the ultra-high-frequency part of her range that I'm starting to suspect she may be an intergalactic spy trying to re- establish communications with the far-off Planet of Dogs.\"<ref name=gettel>{{cite web|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/orlandosentinel/access/89020790.html?dids=89020790:89020790&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Sep+27%2C+1991&author=Parry+Gettelman+of+The+Sentinel+Staff&pub=Orlando+Sentinel&desc=MARIAH+CAREY&pqatl=google|title=Mariah Carey \u2013 Emotions|last=Gettelman|first=Parry|work=[[Orlando Sentinel]]|publisher=[[Tribune Company]]|date=September 21, 1991|accessdate=March 19, 2011}}</ref> Steve Morse from ''[[The Boston Globe]]'' was more enthusiastic in his review, deeming ''Emotions'' \"a quantum leap in maturity and confidence\" from her first album. He called the lyrics \"remarkable,\" the ballads \"unspeakably beautiful,\" and Carey's vocal and songwriting ability \"unlimited.\"<ref name=morse>{{cite web|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-7677501.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105191943/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-7677501.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=November 5, 2012|title=Mariah Carey: On A More Personal Note|last=Morse|first=Steve|work=[[The Boston Globe]]|publisher=The New York Times Company|date=September 17, 1991|accessdate=March 19, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn a retrospective review, ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]'' hailed ''Emotions'' as \"a technically perfect example of mainstream R&B,\" boasting Carey's shapely vocals and \"the customary elegance of a multi-million dollar production.\"<ref name=\"Qmag\">{{cite magazine|magazine=[[Q (magazine)|Q]]|title=Review|page=142|date=November 1999}}</ref> [[AllMusic]] editor Ashley S. Battel called the record a \"musical journey\" and \"strong follow-up\" to Carey's first album that successfully replicated its predecessor's formula of \"dance/R&B/ballads.\" Battel named \"[[Emotions (Mariah Carey song)|Emotions]]\" and \"[[Make It Happen (Mariah Carey song)|Make It Happen]]\" as the album's highlights.<ref name=erlewine>{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r3321|pure_url=yes}}|title=Mariah Carey \u2013 Emotions|last=Battel|first=Ashley S.|work=[[Allmusic]]|publisher=[[All Media Guide]]. [[Rovi Corporation]]|accessdate=March 19, 2011}}</ref> [[Robert Christgau]] remained unimpressed, however, and rated ''Emotions'' a \"dud,\" indicating \"a bad record whose details rarely merit further thought.\"<ref name=\"CG\">{{cite book|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|year=2000|pages=xvi, 49|title=Christgau's Consumer Guide: Albums of the '90s|publisher=[[Macmillan Publishers|Macmillan]]|isbn=0312245602|url=https://archive.org/details/christgausconsum00chri_0|url-access=registration}}</ref>\n\n=== Accolades ===\nThroughout 1992, Carey, the album and its accompanying singles received recognition by the music industry in the form of several awards. At the [[American Music Awards of 1992|19th annual]] [[American Music Award]]s, Carey took home the award for [[American Music Award for Favorite Soul/R&B Female Artist|Favorite Soul/R&B Female Artist]].<ref name=\"shapiro3\">{{harvnb|Shapiro|2001|pp=161\u2013164}}</ref> At the 3rd annual [[Billboard Music Award]]s, Carey took home two trophies for the album and \"Emotions,\" Top Female Album Artist and Top Female Single.<ref name=\"shapiro3\"/> Additionally, Carey was nominated for two [[Grammy Award]] at the [[34th Grammy Awards|34th annual ceremony]], for [[Grammy Award for Producer of the Year, Non-Classical|Producer of the Year]] and [[Grammy Award for Best Female Pop Vocal Performance|Best Female Pop Vocal Performance]], losing in both categories.<ref name=\"shapiro3\"/> All three of the album's singles were awarded [[Broadcast Music Incorporated|BMI Pop Awards]] in 1993.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://repertoire.bmi.com/title.asp?blnWriter=True&blnPublisher=True&blnArtist=True&keyID=371732&ShowNbr=0&ShowSeqNbr=0&querytype=WorkID |title=BMI: Repertoire Search |work=[[BMI Foundation]] |publisher=[[Broadcast Music Incorporated]] |accessdate=March 28, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160111074444/http://repertoire.bmi.com/title.asp?blnWriter=True&blnPublisher=True&blnArtist=True&keyID=371732&ShowNbr=0&ShowSeqNbr=0&querytype=WorkID |archivedate=January 11, 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://repertoire.bmi.com/title.asp?blnWriter=True&blnPublisher=True&blnArtist=True&keyID=176188&ShowNbr=0&ShowSeqNbr=0&querytype=WorkID |title=BMI: Repertoire Search |work=BMI Foundation |publisher=Broadcast Music Incorporated |accessdate=March 28, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151216141710/http://repertoire.bmi.com/title.asp?blnWriter=True&blnPublisher=True&blnArtist=True&keyID=176188&ShowNbr=0&ShowSeqNbr=0&querytype=WorkID |archivedate=December 16, 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://repertoire.bmi.com/title.asp?blnWriter=True&blnPublisher=True&blnArtist=True&keyID=946095&ShowNbr=0&ShowSeqNbr=0&querytype=WorkID |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120720054349/http://repertoire.bmi.com/title.asp?blnWriter=True&blnPublisher=True&blnArtist=True&keyID=946095&ShowNbr=0&ShowSeqNbr=0&querytype=WorkID |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 20, 2012 |title=BMI: Repertoire Search |work=BMI Foundation |publisher=Broadcast Music Incorporated |accessdate=March 28, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n== Commercial performance ==\n[[File:Mariah Carey in August 2006 4.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Carey performing \"[[Make It Happen (Mariah Carey song)|Make It Happen]]\" in Florida, during her [[The Adventures of Mimi Tour|Adventures of Mimi Tour]]]]\n''Emotions'' debuted at the number four position on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], with first-week sales of 129,000 copies, surprising critics following the success of ''[[Mariah Carey (album)|Mariah Carey]]'' (1990). In total, the album spent twenty-seven weeks in the top twenty and a total of fifty-five on the albums chart, becoming Carey's lowest-peaking album until ''[[Glitter (soundtrack)|Glitter]]'' (2001). ''Emotions'' was certified quadruple-[[RIAA certification|Platinum]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA), denoting shipments of four million copies within the United States.<ref name=riaa>{{cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?resultpage=2&table=SEARCH_RESULTS&action=&title=&artist=mariah%20carey&format=ALBUM&debutLP=&category=&sex=&releaseDate=&requestNo=&type=&level=&label=&company=&certificationDate=&awardDescription=&catalogNo=&aSex=&rec_id=&charField=&gold=&platinum=&multiPlat=&level2=&certDate=&album=&id=&after=&before=&startMonth=1&endMonth=1&startYear=1958&endYear=2009&sort=Artist&perPage=25 |title=RIAA Gold & Platinum > Mariah Carey |publisher=Recording Industry Association of America |accessdate=January 14, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130826033505/https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?resultpage=2&table=SEARCH_RESULTS&action=&title=&artist=mariah%20carey&format=ALBUM&debutLP=&category=&sex=&releaseDate=&requestNo=&type=&level=&label=&company=&certificationDate=&awardDescription=&catalogNo=&aSex=&rec_id=&charField=&gold=&platinum=&multiPlat=&level2=&certDate=&album=&id=&after=&before=&startMonth=1&endMonth=1&startYear=1958&endYear=2009&sort=Artist&perPage=25 |archivedate=August 26, 2013 }}</ref> According to [[Nielsen SoundScan]], the album's stateside sales are estimated at 3,595,000.<ref name=\"ussales\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/1555095/ask-billboard-belindas-back-jt-too-mariah-careys-album-sales|title=Ask Billboard: Belinda's Back, JT Too, Mariah Carey's Album Sales & More|last=Trust|first=Gary|date=April 2, 2013|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media |accessdate=May 11, 2013}}</ref> On the [[RPM (magazine)|Canadian ''RPM'' Albums Chart]], ''Emotions'' debuted at number fourteen, on the issue dated October 5, 1991.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.1641&type=1&interval=50&PHPSESSID=4dp17sl7hp9qmhhj3vmcenr836|title=Top Albums/CDs \u2013 Volume 54, No. 18, October 05 1991|magazine=[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]|date=October 5, 1991|accessdate=September 21, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121022035006/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.1641&type=1&interval=50&PHPSESSID=4dp17sl7hp9qmhhj3vmcenr836|archive-date=October 22, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> Four weeks later, on the issue date November 2, 1991, the album reached its peak position of number six, staying there for one week.<ref name=can>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.1665&type=1&interval=50&PHPSESSID=4dp17sl7hp9qmhhj3vmcenr836|title=Top Albums/CDs \u2013 Volume 54, No. 22, November 02 1991|magazine=RPM|date=November 2, 1991|accessdate=September 21, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121018214943/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.1665&type=1&interval=50&PHPSESSID=4dp17sl7hp9qmhhj3vmcenr836|archive-date=October 18, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> At the end of the year, ''Emotions'' finished number 35 on the Year-End Albums Chart of 1991.<ref name=canend>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.1702&type=1&interval=50&PHPSESSID=4dp17sl7hp9qmhhj3vmcenr836|title=RPM 100 Albums of 1991|magazine=RPM|date=December 21, 1991|accessdate=September 21, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121022035034/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.1702&type=1&interval=50&PHPSESSID=4dp17sl7hp9qmhhj3vmcenr836|archive-date=October 22, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> To date, the album has been certified quadruple-[[List of music recording certifications|platinum]] by the [[Canadian Recording Industry Association]] (CRIA), denoting shipments of 400,000 units.<ref name=\"Canadian Certification database\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cria.ca/cert_db_search.php |title=CRIA: Certification Results \u2013 Mariah Carey |publisher=[[Canadian Recording Industry Association]] |accessdate=August 19, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090412081617/http://www.cria.ca/cert_db_search.php |archivedate=April 12, 2009 }}</ref> In Japan, ''Emotions'' debuted at number three on the official [[Oricon]] chart, and according to [[Sony Music Entertainment|Sony Music]], has shipped 1,000,000 copies throughout the country.<ref name=jap>{{cite web|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/prof/artist/163336/ranking/cd_album/|title=Profile of Mariah Carey|language=Japanese|publisher=[[Oricon]]. [[Recording Industry Association of Japan]]|accessdate=September 21, 2010}}</ref><ref name=sales>{{cite web|url=http://www.sonymusic.co.jp/Music/International/Arch/SR/MariahCarey/SICP-8076/index.html|title=Mariah Carey: Emotions|language=Japanese|work=[[Sony Music Entertainment Japan]]|publisher=[[Sony]]|accessdate=March 19, 2011}}</ref> In Australia, the album debuted at number ninety-six on the [[ARIA Charts|ARIA Albums Chart]] during the week ending October 6, 1991, attaining its peak position of number eight four weeks later.<ref name=aus>{{cite web|url=http://australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Mariah+Carey&titel=Emotions&cat=a|title=Mariah Carey \u2013 Emotions|work=[[ARIA Charts]]|publisher=Hung Medien|accessdate=March 19, 2011}}</ref> The album spent thirty weeks in the top 100, being certified Platinum by the [[Australian Recording Industry Association]] (ARIA).<ref name=ryan/>\n\nIn France, ''Emotions'' received a gold certifications from the [[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique]] (SNEP), denoting shipments of 100,000 units.<ref name=snep>{{cite web|url=http://www.infodisc.fr/Certif_Album.php |title=Les Certifications > Mariah Carey |publisher=InfoDisc |language=French |accessdate=April 2, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100621054859/http://www.infodisc.fr/Certif_Album.php |archivedate=June 21, 2010 }}</ref> The album made its debut on the [[Dutch Top 40]] at number seventy-nine.<ref name=neth>{{cite web|url=http://dutchcharts.nl/showitem.asp?interpret=Mariah+Carey&titel=Emotions&cat=a|title=Mariah Carey \u2013 Emotions|work=[[Dutch Top 40]]|publisher=Hung Medien|accessdate=March 19, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AcxCpZH0?url=http://dutchcharts.nl/showitem.asp?interpret=Mariah+Carey&titel=Emotions&cat=a|archivedate=September 12, 2012}}</ref> The following week, it moved up to number fifty-nine, which became its peak charting position.<ref name=neth/> In total, ''Emotions'' spent six weeks within the Dutch charts, being certified Platinum by the [[NVPI|Nederlandse Vereniging van Producenten en Importeurs van beeld- en geluidsdragers]] (NVPI), denoting shipments of 100,000 units.<ref name=nether>{{cite web|url=http://www.nvpi.nl/nvpi/pagina.asp?pagkey=61112&documentid=1237686&zoekform=60463&formposted=yes |title=Mariah Carey&nbsp;\u2013 Emotions |publisher=[[NVPI|Nederlandse Vereniging van Producenten en Importeurs van beeld- en geluidsdragers]] |date= |accessdate=August 25, 2010 }}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> During the week of October 17, 1991, ''Emotions'' debuted at its peak position of number six, spending a total of sixteen weeks on the [[Recording Industry Association of New Zealand|New Zealand Albums Chart]].<ref name=new>{{cite web|url=https://charts.nz/showitem.asp?interpret=Mariah+Carey&titel=Emotions&cat=a|title=Mariah Carey \u2013 Emotions|work=[[Recording Industry Association of New Zealand|New Zealand Singles Chart]]|publisher=Hung Medien|accessdate=March 19, 2011}}</ref> The [[Recording Industry Association of New Zealand]] (RIANZ) certified the album Platinum, denoting shipments of 15,000 units within the country.<ref name=\"scapolo\">{{cite book | author=Scapolo, Dean| title=The Complete New Zealand Music Charts 1966\u20132006 | publisher=RIANZ| year=2007 | isbn=978-1-877443-00-8}}</ref> In Sweden, ''Emotions'' debuted at number twenty-six on the [[Sverigetopplistan|Swedish Albums Chart]], peaking at number thirteen and spending a total of five weeks fluctuating in the chart.<ref name=swe>{{cite web|url=http://swedishcharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Mariah+Carey&titel=Emotions&cat=a|title=Mariah Carey \u2013 Emotions|work=[[Sverigetopplistan]]|publisher=Hung Medien|accessdate=March 19, 2011}}</ref> Following its exit from the chart, the album was certified Platinum by the [[International Federation of the Phonographic Industry]] (IFPI), denoting shipments of 100,000 units.<ref name=\"Swedish Certifications 1987-1998\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.ifpi.se/wp/wp-content/uploads/guld-platina-1987-1998.pdf |title=Guld & Platina IFPI |trans-title=Swedish Certifications 1987\u20131998 |language=Swedish |publisher=International Federation of the Phonographic Industry \u2013 Sweden |accessdate=August 19, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120521214300/http://www.ifpi.se/wp/wp-content/uploads/guld-platina-1987-1998.pdf |archivedate=May 21, 2012 }}</ref> On October 13, 1991, ''Emotions'' debuted at number sixteen on the [[Swiss Music Charts|Swiss Albums Chart]], attaining its peak position of fifteen the succeeding week.<ref name=swi>{{cite web|url=http://hitparade.ch/showitem.asp?interpret=Mariah+Carey&titel=Emotions&cat=a|title=Mariah Carey \u2013 Emotions|work=[[Swiss Music Charts]]|publisher=Hung Medien|accessdate=March 19, 2011}}</ref> Following a run of nine weeks in the albums chart, the album was certified gold by the IFPI, denoting shipments of 50,000 units throughout the country.<ref name=\"Swiss Certifications 1991\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.swisscharts.com/awards.asp?year=1991|title=Awards 1994|publisher=International Federation of the Phonographic Industry \u2014 Switzerland|accessdate=August 19, 2010}}</ref> On the [[UK Albums Chart]], dated October 26, 1991, the album debuted at number ten.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theofficialcharts.com/archive-chart/_/3/1991-10-26/|title=Top 40 Official UK Singles Archive|work=[[The Official Charts Company]]|publisher=[[British Phonographic Industry]]|date=October 26, 1991|accessdate=November 28, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AcxIGTDM?url=http://www.officialcharts.com/archive-chart/_/3/1991-10-26/|archivedate=September 12, 2012}}</ref> In its seventeenth week, ''Emotions'' attained its peak position of number four, placing higher than Carey's debut reach of six.<ref name=\"Top 40 Official UK Singles Archive\">{{cite web|url=http://www.theofficialcharts.com/archive-chart/_/3/1992-02-15/|title=Top 40 Official UK Singles Archive|work=The Official Charts Company|publisher=British Phonographic Industry|date=February 15, 1992|accessdate=November 28, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AcxJ0FlF?url=http://www.officialcharts.com/archive-chart/_/3/1992-02-15/|archivedate=September 12, 2012}}</ref> After charting in the United Kingdom for forty weeks, the album was certified Platinum by the [[British Phonographic Industry]] (BPI), denoting shipments of 300,000 units.<ref name=bpi>{{cite web|url=http://www.bpi.co.uk/certifiedawards/search.aspx |title=BPI \u2013 Certified Awards |publisher=British Phonographic Industry |accessdate=August 13, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5mr0Evm3j?url=http://www.bpi.co.uk/certifiedawards/search.aspx |archivedate=January 17, 2010 }}</ref> ''Emotions'' has sold 8 million copies worldwide, short of the 15 million sold by her debut in 1990.<ref name=\"globalsales\">{{cite web|url=https://www.vibe.com/2017/02/chance-the-rapper-best-new-artist-grammy-awards-past-winners/new-york-chapter-of-the-recording-academy-honors-2005/|title=Mariah Carey \u2013 York Chapter Recording|first=Camille|last=Augustin|work=[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]|date=February 13, 2017|accessdate=November 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Track listing ==\n{{Track listing\n| extra_column  = Producer(s)\n| all_lyrics    = Mariah Carey\n| title1        = [[Emotions (Mariah Carey song)|Emotions]]\n| music1        = {{hlist|Carey|[[Robert Clivill\u00e9s]]|[[David Cole (producer)|David Cole]]}}\n| extra1        = {{hlist|Clivill\u00e9s|Cole|Carey}}\n| length1       = 4:09\n| title2        = And You Don't Remember\n| music2        = {{hlist|Carey|[[Walter Afanasieff]]}}\n| extra2        = {{hlist|Carey|Afanasieff}}\n| length2       = 4:26\n| title3        = [[Can't Let Go (Mariah Carey song)|Can't Let Go]]\n| music3        = {{hlist|Carey|Afanasieff}}\n| extra3        = {{hlist|Carey|Afanasieff}}\n| length3       = 4:27\n| title4        = [[Make It Happen (Mariah Carey song)|Make It Happen]]\n| music4        = {{hlist|Carey|Clivill\u00e9s|Cole}}\n| extra4        = {{hlist|Carey|Clivill\u00e9s|Cole}}\n| length4       = 5:10\n| title5        = [[If It's Over]]\n| music5         = {{hlist|Carey|[[Carole King]]}}\n| extra5        = {{hlist|Carey|Afanasieff}}\n| length5       = 4:38\n| title6        = You're So Cold\n| music6        = {{hlist|Carey|Cole}}\n| extra6        = {{hlist|Carey|Clivill\u00e9s|Cole}}\n| length6       = 5:05\n| title7        = So Blessed\n| music7        = {{hlist|Carey|Afanasieff}}\n| extra7        = {{hlist|Carey|Afanasieff}}\n| length7       = 4:13\n| title8        = To Be Around You\n| music8        = {{hlist|Carey|Cole}}\n| extra8        = {{hlist|Carey|Clivill\u00e9s|Cole}}\n| length8       = 4:37\n| title9        = Till the End of Time\n| music9        = {{hlist|Carey|Afanasieff}}\n| extra9        = {{hlist|Carey|Afanasieff}}\n| length9       = 5:35\n| title10       = The Wind\n| music10       = {{hlist|Carey|[[Russ Freeman (pianist)|Russell Freeman]]}}\n| extra10       = Carey\n| length10      = 4:41\n}}\n\n'''Sample credits'''\n* \"Can't Let Go\" contains a sample of \"[[Make It Last Forever (song)|Make It Last Forever]]\" by [[Keith Sweat]] and Jacci McGhee (1987)\n* \"Make It Happen\" contains a sample of \"I Want to Thank You\" by [[Alicia Myers]] (1981)\n* \"The Wind\" contains a sample of \"The Wind\" by [[Chet Baker]] and [[Russ Freeman (pianist)|Russell Freeman]] (1954)\n\n== Personnel ==\nCredits for ''Emotions'' adapted from [[AllMusic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/r3321|title=Mariah Carey \u2013 Emotions: Credits|work=Allmusic|publisher=All Media Guide. Rovi Corporation|accessdate=March 19, 2011}}</ref>\n{{Div col|colwidth=35em}}\n* [[Mariah Carey]] \u2013 [[Arrangement|arranger]], [[Audio mixing (recorded music)|mixing]], [[Record producer|producer]], [[Singing|vocal arrangement]], [[Singing|vocals]], [[Backing vocalist|background vocals]]\n* [[Walter Afanasieff]] \u2013 [[acoustic guitar]], arranger, [[Bass (sound)|bass]], [[Drum kit|drums]], [[French horn|horn arrangements]], grand [[piano]], [[Keyboard instrument|keyboards]], [[Organ (music)|organ]], [[Hammond organ|organ (Hammond)]], [[Percussion instrument|percussion]], piano, producer, programming, [[String instrument|strings]], [[synclavier]], [[synthesizer]], synthesizer bass, [[tambourine]], [[vibraphone]], vocal arrangement\n* Vernon \"Ice\" Black \u2013 guitar\n* Bruce Calder \u2013 assistant engineer\n* Dana Jon Chappelle \u2013 engineer, mixing\n* Gary Cirimelli \u2013 programming, synclavier\n* [[Robert Clivill\u00e9s]] \u2013 arranger, drums, keyboard arrangements, mixing, producer\n* [[David Cole (producer)|David Cole]] \u2013 arranger, background vocals, keyboard arrangements, keyboards, mixing, producer\n* Lew Del Gatto \u2013 baritone saxophone, horn arrangements\n* Josephine DiDonato \u2013 art direction\n* Phillip Dixon \u2013 photography\n* [[Cornell Dupree]] \u2013 guitar\n* Lawrence Feldman \u2013 [[Saxophone|tenor saxophone]]\n* [[Alan Friedman]] \u2013 programming\n* [[Earl Gardner (musician)|Earl Gardner]] \u2013 trumpet\n* Lolly Grodner \u2013 assistant engineer\n* Carl James \u2013 bass guitar\n* Acar S. Key \u2013 engineer\n* [[Ren Klyce]] \u2013 programming, synclavier, synthesizer\n* Manny Lacarrubba \u2013 assistant engineer\n* [[Michael Landau]] \u2013 guitar\n* [[Will Lee (bassist)|Will Lee]] \u2013 bass\n* [[Trey Lorenz]] \u2013 background vocals\n* [[Bob Ludwig]] \u2013 mastering\n* Jon Mathias \u2013 engineer\n* Patrique McMillian \u2013 background vocals\n* Bruce Miller \u2013 engineer\n* Cindy Mizelle \u2013 background vocals\n* [[Tommy Mottola]] \u2013 executive producer\n* Keith O'Quinn \u2013 trombone\n* [[Paul Pesco]] \u2013 guitar\n* [[Bob Rosa]] \u2013 mixing\n* [[Craig Silvey]] \u2013 assistant engineer\n* M.T. Silvia \u2013 assistant engineer\n* [[Steve Smith (musician)|Steve Smith]] \u2013 drums\n* George Young \u2013 tenor saxophone\n{{div col end}}\n\n== Charts ==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align: